00:29:17,588 --> 00:29:21,456
The president was enjoying
his final year in office.

536
00:29:21,492 --> 00:29:23,790
But as the economy
started to fall apart,

537
00:29:23,828 --> 00:29:27,958
he decided it was time
to roll out the C word.

538
00:29:27,999 --> 00:29:31,025
Capitalism is the best system
ever devised.

539
00:29:31,069 --> 00:29:32,468
Really?

540
00:29:32,503 --> 00:29:35,768
Voices from the left and right
are equating the free enterprise system

541
00:29:35,807 --> 00:29:39,470
with greed and exploitation
and failure.

542
00:29:39,910 --> 00:29:41,501
Greed,

543
00:29:41,546 --> 00:29:44,709
exploitation, failure?

544
00:29:44,749 --> 00:29:46,273
Go on, I'm listening.

545
00:29:46,317 --> 00:29:51,186
Capitalism offers people
the freedom to choose

546
00:29:51,222 --> 00:29:53,782
where they work
and what they do...

547
00:29:53,825 --> 00:29:56,521
Pat Andrews
has been looking for work.

548
00:29:56,561 --> 00:30:00,429
Every morning she scans
the classifieds in vain.

549
00:30:00,465 --> 00:30:02,228
There isn't anything in here.

550
00:30:02,266 --> 00:30:05,201
I'm not gonna be a gentleman's club
hired dancer either.

551
00:30:06,537 --> 00:30:10,029
...the opportunity to buy
or sell products they want.

552
00:30:10,074 --> 00:30:12,008
Tom Rendon has avoided layoffs

553
00:30:12,043 --> 00:30:14,705
at his sign company
in Stockton, California,

554
00:30:14,746 --> 00:30:16,646
all because this one word
now makes up

555
00:30:16,681 --> 00:30:18,740
for half his business.

556
00:30:18,783 --> 00:30:22,344
If you seek social justice
and human dignity,

557
00:30:22,387 --> 00:30:26,221
the free market system
is the way to go.

558
00:30:29,093 --> 00:30:32,221
And for those seeking
justice in Pennsylvania,

559
00:30:32,263 --> 00:30:36,165
free enterprise
was definitely the way to go.

560
00:30:39,670 --> 00:30:41,331
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania,

561
00:30:41,372 --> 00:30:43,533
has one of the highest rates
in the state

562
00:30:43,574 --> 00:30:47,203
of young people locked up
in the juvenile home.

563
00:30:47,245 --> 00:30:49,577
Perhaps it's because
the good people here

564
00:30:49,614 --> 00:30:51,980
employ the practices
of capitalism

565
00:30:52,016 --> 00:30:55,247
in dealing with
their wayward youth.

566
00:30:55,286 --> 00:30:58,187
The county hired a private
profit-making corporation

567
00:30:58,222 --> 00:31:02,352
with a sweet-sounding name,
PA Child Care.

568
00:31:03,594 --> 00:31:06,529
It was owned and run
by 2 businessmen,

569
00:31:06,564 --> 00:31:11,228
one of whom was Robert Powell,
an attorney and entrepreneur.

570
00:31:11,269 --> 00:31:13,203
His good friend Judge Conahan

571
00:31:13,237 --> 00:31:15,603
closed down
the public juvenile home

572
00:31:15,640 --> 00:31:17,574
and then got
PA Child Care to build

573
00:31:17,608 --> 00:31:20,771
an $8 million
privately-owned facility

574
00:31:20,812 --> 00:31:22,712
and charge it back to the county

575
00:31:22,747 --> 00:31:25,443
for a mere $58 million lease.

576
00:31:27,385 --> 00:31:31,014
Let's meet some of Wilkes-Barre's
juvenile delinquents.

577
00:31:31,055 --> 00:31:33,353
Magee smoked pot
at a high school party.

578
00:31:33,391 --> 00:31:36,622
I was very rebellious
when I was at this age.

579
00:31:36,661 --> 00:31:39,459
Matt, he got into
an argument at the dinner table.

580
00:31:39,497 --> 00:31:42,159
I threw a piece of meat,
as in steak,

581
00:31:42,200 --> 00:31:44,668
cooked dinner,
at my mother's boyfriend.

582
00:31:44,702 --> 00:31:47,068
Jamie got in a fight
at a shopping mall

583
00:31:47,105 --> 00:31:48,367
with her best friend.

584
00:31:48,406 --> 00:31:51,842
I just figured, you know, we just weren't
gonna be friends anymore.

585
00:31:51,876 --> 00:31:54,401
And Hillary made
a MySpace page

586
00:31:54,445 --> 00:31:56,606
making fun
of her assistant principal

587
00:31:56,647 --> 00:31:59,138
for being strict and having
no sense of humor.

588
00:31:59,183 --> 00:32:02,619
And it said some pretty silly,
like, 14-year-old-girl stuff.

589
00:32:02,653 --> 00:32:06,384
Her assistant principal
called the police.

590
00:32:06,424 --> 00:32:10,724
They all appeared before
kindly Judge Mark Ciavarella.

591
00:32:10,761 --> 00:32:13,491
These kids were about
to get their first lesson

592
00:32:13,531 --> 00:32:15,499
in American capitalism:

593
00:32:15,533 --> 00:32:20,334
time is money, lots of money.

594
00:32:20,371 --> 00:32:23,670
I went in front of the court,
in front of Mr. Ciavarella,

595
00:32:23,708 --> 00:32:25,505
and I wasn't even in front of him
for 4 minutes.

596
00:32:25,543 --> 00:32:27,636
I was only in front of him
for, like, 2 minutes.

597
00:32:27,678 --> 00:32:31,307
The first thing that
Judge Ciavarella said to me was,

598
00:32:31,349 --> 00:32:34,216
"What makes you think
you can do this kind of crap?"

599
00:32:34,252 --> 00:32:36,686
I'm sure he knew in his mind
when I walked in

600
00:32:36,721 --> 00:32:38,484
that he was locking this kid up
no matter what.

601
00:32:38,523 --> 00:32:39,820
He didn't even look at me.

602
00:32:39,857 --> 00:32:42,826
Once I entered the courtroom,
I didn't have any chance.

603
00:32:42,860 --> 00:32:45,124
There was about 6 kids
who went in front of me.

604
00:32:45,163 --> 00:32:47,188
Every single kid who went
in front of Ciavarella,

605
00:32:47,231 --> 00:32:50,598
for all different reasons--
some minor, some serious--

606
00:32:50,635 --> 00:32:52,330
got sent away.

607
00:32:52,370 --> 00:32:56,272
Although Wilkes-Barre is located
in the United States of America,

608
00:32:56,307 --> 00:33:00,437
here capitalism
trumped democracy.

609
00:33:00,478 --> 00:33:03,709
Robert Powell, one of the owners
of PA Child Care,

610
00:33:03,748 --> 00:33:08,151
cut a business deal with Judge Conahan
and Judge Ciavarella.

611
00:33:08,186 --> 00:33:11,622
Judge Ciavarella then stepped up
his conviction rates.

612
00:33:11,656 --> 00:33:13,385
Many of these kids
were funneled

613
00:33:13,424 --> 00:33:18,191
into PA Child Care's
for-profit juvenile facility.

614
00:33:18,229 --> 00:33:19,628
And for their troubles,

615
00:33:19,664 --> 00:33:23,862
the judges received
over $2.6 million

616
00:33:23,901 --> 00:33:27,860
while the owners of PA Child Care
received tens of millions

617
00:33:27,905 --> 00:33:30,499
of taxpayer dollars
from the county.

618
00:33:30,541 --> 00:33:33,669
And where did Powell go
to enjoy all that money?

619
00:33:33,711 --> 00:33:35,906
On his private plane

620
00:33:35,947 --> 00:33:39,007
and his yacht,
the "Reel Justice."

621
00:33:40,685 --> 00:33:45,588
6,500 children
were unjustly convicted.

622
00:33:45,623 --> 00:33:49,024
It was good business
while it lasted.

623
00:33:50,161 --> 00:33:53,028
2 Luzerne County judges
in big trouble with the law.

624
00:33:53,064 --> 00:33:54,053
They're going to jail.

625
00:33:54,098 --> 00:33:55,531
Some kids were locked up

626
00:33:55,566 --> 00:33:59,832
even when probation officers
objected to detention.

627
00:33:59,870 --> 00:34:02,862
In there you lose track of time
and you lose track of the date.

628
00:34:02,907 --> 00:34:04,135
I was barely keeping track.

629
00:34:04,175 --> 00:34:07,303
It was supposed to be, like--
I believe it was, like, 2 months.

630
00:34:07,345 --> 00:34:09,745
And it went from 2 months
to 9 months.

631
00:34:09,780 --> 00:34:12,476
He said originally
3 to 6 months,

632
00:34:12,516 --> 00:34:16,509
but somehow I ended up
being there 11½ months

633
00:34:16,554 --> 00:34:19,387
and I never went back
in front of the judge at all

634
00:34:19,423 --> 00:34:21,050
for him to give me extensions.

635
00:34:21,092 --> 00:34:22,889
Not only did PA Child Care

636
00:34:22,927 --> 00:34:25,760
pay off the judges
to fill their cells,

637
00:34:25,796 --> 00:34:28,458
but their employees were the ones
who got to decide

638
00:34:28,499 --> 00:34:31,900
when a child had
enough rehabilitation.

639
00:34:31,936 --> 00:34:35,269
But that makes sense,
because any time a governmental unit

640
00:34:35,306 --> 00:34:37,866
turns over to
a profit-making corporation

641
00:34:37,908 --> 00:34:40,308
the duties it should be performing,

642
00:34:40,344 --> 00:34:42,369
what do you expect to happen?

643
00:34:42,413 --> 00:34:45,007
It makes me feel like
an item that they just used

644
00:34:45,049 --> 00:34:47,449
to just get money
and then tossed me aside.

645
00:34:47,485 --> 00:34:51,945
I'm just trying
to work on my flying

646
00:34:51,989 --> 00:34:54,184
and just trying to prepare
for my future

647
00:34:54,225 --> 00:34:57,456
so I can put this all behind me,
finally be done with all this.

648
00:34:57,495 --> 00:34:59,963
During the whole trial
I wasn't in control at all,

649
00:34:59,997 --> 00:35:02,431
but with flying it's only me.

650
00:35:02,466 --> 00:35:04,934
It's just that I just get
to do everything by myself.

651
00:35:04,969 --> 00:35:06,994
I'm the only one on the control.

652
00:35:07,038 --> 00:35:08,869
Matt loves to fly

653
00:35:08,906 --> 00:35:12,171
and hopes to become
a pilot someday.

654
00:35:12,209 --> 00:35:14,837
If he does,
he'll get his 2nd lesson

655
00:35:14,879 --> 00:35:17,473
in capitalism:

656
00:35:17,515 --> 00:35:20,541
that in America,
sometimes you're better off

657
00:35:20,584 --> 00:35:23,020
working at Mickey D's.

658
00:35:23,520 --> 00:35:25,580
Remember Sully?

659
00:35:25,623 --> 00:35:26,954
Captain Sullenberger,

660
00:35:26,991 --> 00:35:30,017
who safely landed an airbus
in the Hudson River

661
00:35:30,061 --> 00:35:32,287
saving the lives of 150 passengers?

662
00:35:33,930 --> 00:35:35,997
A true American hero.

663
00:35:39,136 --> 00:35:42,037
He met the mayor.
He went to the State of the Union.

664
00:35:42,073 --> 00:35:44,769
Heck, he even went
to the Super Bowl.

665
00:35:44,809 --> 00:35:47,039
And then he went to Congress.

666
00:35:47,078 --> 00:35:50,138
Flying has been my lifelong passion.

667
00:35:50,181 --> 00:35:52,342
But while I love my profession,

668
00:35:52,383 --> 00:35:55,079
I do not like
what has happened to it.

669
00:35:55,319 --> 00:35:57,212
It is my personal experience

670
00:35:57,254 --> 00:36:00,451
that my decision to remain
in the profession I love

671
00:36:00,491 --> 00:36:05,121
has come at a great financial cost
to me and to my family.

672
00:36:05,162 --> 00:36:07,426
My pay has been cut 40%.

673
00:36:07,465 --> 00:36:11,128
My pension, like most airline pensions,
has been terminated.

674
00:36:11,168 --> 00:36:14,695
So please do not think I exaggerate
when I say that I do not know

675
00:36:14,739 --> 00:36:18,038
a single professional airline pilot
who wants his or her children

676
00:36:18,075 --> 00:36:19,667
to follow in their footsteps.

677
00:36:20,210 --> 00:36:22,440
You cleared the room
with that one, Sully.

678
00:36:22,480 --> 00:36:24,778
I don't think the congressmen
wanted to hear that stuff.

679
00:36:24,815 --> 00:36:27,750
- They like you as a hero.
- The current experience...

680
00:36:42,333 --> 00:36:44,392
What was your starting pay as a pilot?

681
00:36:44,435 --> 00:36:46,733
I made $19,000 the first year.

682
00:36:46,771 --> 00:36:50,229
I was bumped up to about 22,000
or 23,000 the second year.

683
00:36:50,274 --> 00:36:52,902
Last year, gross pay

684
00:36:52,943 --> 00:36:55,377
I made $17,600.

685
00:36:55,413 --> 00:36:58,007
There's a joke in the airline
when we get our wings pinned on us

686
00:36:58,048 --> 00:37:01,506
as new-hire airline pilots
that the company just kinda says,

687
00:37:01,552 --> 00:37:04,316
"Hey, don't apply for food stamps
in your uniform."

688
00:37:04,355 --> 00:37:07,222
I don't know about you,
but I want the pilot

689
00:37:07,258 --> 00:37:11,058
who's got me 30,000 feet up in the air
to be paid really well

690
00:37:11,095 --> 00:37:14,155
and not sitting up in the cockpit
digging through the pilot's seat

691
00:37:14,198 --> 00:37:16,189
looking for loose change.

692
00:37:16,233 --> 00:37:18,201
There was a period
of about 4 months

693
00:37:18,235 --> 00:37:20,999
where I was on food stamps.

694
00:37:21,038 --> 00:37:22,528
- You were on food stamps?
- Yes.

695
00:37:22,573 --> 00:37:25,337
- And you were still flying the plane?
- Yes.

696
00:37:25,376 --> 00:37:27,742
With my--
with my food stamp card.

697
00:37:27,778 --> 00:37:30,542
The lady I talked to
in the food stamp office,

698
00:37:30,581 --> 00:37:33,516
when I told her I was a pilot,
she didn't bat an eye,

699
00:37:33,551 --> 00:37:35,883
but she didn't--
I knew she didn't believe me.

700
00:37:35,920 --> 00:37:38,548
How have you gotten by?
How have you been able to afford things?

701
00:37:38,589 --> 00:37:41,183
Relying on credit cards
to buy the groceries at times

702
00:37:41,225 --> 00:37:42,954
- when I wasn't on food stamps.
- Really?

703
00:37:42,993 --> 00:37:45,291
I have about $10,000
in credit card debt

704
00:37:45,329 --> 00:37:47,320
just on the necessities,

705
00:37:47,364 --> 00:37:49,924
not on the big-screen TV
and the stereo.

706
00:37:49,967 --> 00:37:53,164
You're using it to buy
your groceries and get by.

707
00:37:53,204 --> 00:37:55,138
- Yes.
- Do you have any student loan debt?

708
00:37:55,172 --> 00:37:56,867
- Yes.
- How much?

709
00:37:56,907 --> 00:37:58,465
Mine is about 80,000.

710
00:37:58,509 --> 00:38:01,910
- I took out $100,000.
- Student loans?

711
00:38:01,946 --> 00:38:04,813
And by the time I pay it back,
at this rate,

712
00:38:04,849 --> 00:38:07,215
it'll probably cost me well over
a half a million with interest

713
00:38:07,251 --> 00:38:09,811
and fees and penalties.

714
00:38:09,854 --> 00:38:12,084
It's something that I don't--
I don't like to spend a lot of time

715
00:38:12,122 --> 00:38:13,817
thinking about
because it's abysmal.

716
00:38:13,858 --> 00:38:16,326
It's one way that I get down
really quickly

717
00:38:16,360 --> 00:38:18,021
about my chosen career field

718
00:38:18,062 --> 00:38:20,496
is to think about how much I owe
and how little I make.

719
00:38:20,531 --> 00:38:23,432
Have you had to work
a 2nd job to make ends meet?

720
00:38:23,467 --> 00:38:25,833
I walk dogs on the side,

721
00:38:25,870 --> 00:38:29,067
I distribute MonaVie Juice.

722
00:38:29,106 --> 00:38:32,371
I have known pilots
to donate plasma

723
00:38:32,409 --> 00:38:34,240
for extra cash.

724
00:38:34,278 --> 00:38:37,145
- You mean they give blood?
- They-- well--

725
00:38:37,181 --> 00:38:39,809
So they can make extra money
even though they're flying an airplane?

726
00:38:39,850 --> 00:38:41,841
Yeah.
They donate their plasma.

727
00:38:41,886 --> 00:38:46,152
So they get the blood back,
but you can get paid for plasma.

728
00:38:46,190 --> 00:38:47,487
I see.

729
00:38:47,525 --> 00:38:49,322
They suck the blood out of you,
take the plasma...

730
00:38:49,360 --> 00:38:50,827
- Give you the blood back.
- ...give you the--

731
00:38:50,861 --> 00:38:52,726
Well then,
not such a bad deal.

732
00:38:52,763 --> 00:38:56,255
The only reason people stay flying
is because they love it.

733
00:38:56,300 --> 00:38:58,165
And managements
take advantage of that.

734
00:38:58,202 --> 00:39:01,535
The airlines
have managed to farm out

735
00:39:01,572 --> 00:39:05,975
a lot of the flying to commuters

736
00:39:06,010 --> 00:39:09,207
in an effort to basically
bust the unions.

737
00:39:09,246 --> 00:39:11,339
You can't compete

738
00:39:11,382 --> 00:39:15,614
to a lower and lower level
every year

739
00:39:15,653 --> 00:39:18,053
without skimping
on safety somehow.

