00:39:25,195 --> 00:39:27,925
Continental connection flight 3407

742
00:39:27,965 --> 00:39:30,559
began its descent
to the airport in Buffalo.

743
00:39:32,336 --> 00:39:34,201
Stand by, there's some
ground communication,

744
00:39:34,238 --> 00:39:36,138
either state police
or sheriff's department.

745
00:39:36,173 --> 00:39:37,868
We need to find out if anything
is on the ground.

746
00:39:37,908 --> 00:39:40,308
This aircraft was 5 miles out,
and all of a sudden

747
00:39:40,344 --> 00:39:42,175
we have no response
to that aircraft.

748
00:39:42,212 --> 00:39:45,204
All I could tell you is there was
an aircraft over the marker

749
00:39:45,249 --> 00:39:48,275
and we're not talking to them now.

750
00:39:48,319 --> 00:39:50,480
No one survived the crash

751
00:39:50,521 --> 00:39:53,456
and 50 people lost their lives.

752
00:39:54,992 --> 00:39:58,257
The media focused
on the actions of the pilots.

753
00:39:58,295 --> 00:40:01,355
Captain Marvin Renslow
and First Officer Shaw

754
00:40:01,398 --> 00:40:03,628
were chatting about their careers.

755
00:40:03,667 --> 00:40:06,033
"Careers" is a euphemism

756
00:40:06,070 --> 00:40:08,470
for what the pilots
were really talking about:

757
00:40:08,505 --> 00:40:12,635
how little they were paid
and how overworked they were.

758
00:40:12,676 --> 00:40:14,769
There would be
no discussion in the media

759
00:40:14,812 --> 00:40:17,076
about why we have
an economic system

760
00:40:17,114 --> 00:40:20,743
that allows a pilot to be paid less
than a manager at Taco Bell.

761
00:40:20,784 --> 00:40:22,183
First Officer Shaw

762
00:40:22,219 --> 00:40:25,848
made between
$16,000 and $20,000 a year

763
00:40:25,889 --> 00:40:29,450
and at one point
worked a second job.

764
00:40:29,493 --> 00:40:31,927
Her 2nd job had been waitressing

765
00:40:31,962 --> 00:40:33,953
at a coffee shop.

766
00:40:35,265 --> 00:40:38,792
How are these companies
able to get away with this?

767
00:40:38,836 --> 00:40:41,532
I guess that's the point of capitalism.

768
00:40:41,572 --> 00:40:44,336
It allows you to get away
with anything,

769
00:40:44,375 --> 00:40:47,745
like making a profit
off the death of an employee.

770
00:40:49,313 --> 00:40:51,679
Sweetie, I can open it.
Let's try it with this.

771
00:40:51,715 --> 00:40:53,774
This is Irma Johnson.

772
00:40:53,817 --> 00:40:56,786
Irma's husband Dan
worked in middle management

773
00:40:56,820 --> 00:40:58,981
at Amegy Bank in Houston, Texas.

774
00:40:59,023 --> 00:41:01,082
- Wanna try to spread it?
- No.

775
00:41:01,125 --> 00:41:03,650
Dan recently died of cancer,

776
00:41:03,694 --> 00:41:07,926
leaving behind Irma
and their 2 sons.

777
00:41:07,965 --> 00:41:10,525
But unbeknownst to Irma,
Amegy had taken out

778
00:41:10,567 --> 00:41:14,526
a secret life insurance policy
on Dan's life.

779
00:41:14,571 --> 00:41:18,803
The bank generously named itself
as the beneficiary

780
00:41:18,842 --> 00:41:21,333
in the event of Dan's death.

781
00:41:21,378 --> 00:41:24,506
The insurance company
then accidentally informed Irma

782
00:41:24,548 --> 00:41:28,678
that Amegy Bank had received
a check for $1½ million

783
00:41:28,719 --> 00:41:31,654
just weeks after Dan died.

784
00:41:31,689 --> 00:41:33,486
Thank you for helping.

785
00:41:33,524 --> 00:41:34,582
They never told me.

786
00:41:34,625 --> 00:41:38,152
I wanted to find out, well,
why did they purchase a policy for him?

787
00:41:38,195 --> 00:41:40,129
- You didn't know about it?
- No.

788
00:41:40,164 --> 00:41:43,827
And they named themselves
as the beneficiary.

789
00:41:43,867 --> 00:41:44,856
Yeah.

790
00:41:44,902 --> 00:41:47,063
So your husband's death

791
00:41:47,104 --> 00:41:50,073
made them $1.5 million richer?

792
00:41:52,409 --> 00:41:55,936
I know it's not right
for them to try to profit

793
00:41:55,979 --> 00:41:58,413
from my husband's death.

794
00:41:58,449 --> 00:42:00,246
When I first realized
what was happening,

795
00:42:00,284 --> 00:42:04,345
I was in disbelief.

796
00:42:04,388 --> 00:42:07,118
- It's hurtful.
- I'm so sorry.

797
00:42:12,529 --> 00:42:16,124
it's hurtful and I wanted answers.

798
00:42:16,166 --> 00:42:18,828
Irma contacted Michael D. Myers,

799
00:42:18,869 --> 00:42:21,360
a local attorney who had
already been looking into

800
00:42:21,405 --> 00:42:24,704
these kind of corporate
insurance policies on their employees.

801
00:42:26,110 --> 00:42:28,704
With the normal use of life insurance,
where you're guarding against

802
00:42:28,746 --> 00:42:33,308
the loss of a loved one
or a breadwinner of the family,

803
00:42:33,350 --> 00:42:37,753
you don't want that person to die.

804
00:42:37,788 --> 00:42:39,949
With these policies,
the companies that buy these

805
00:42:39,990 --> 00:42:41,855
want the employees to die

806
00:42:41,892 --> 00:42:44,588
in accordance
with the policy projections.

807
00:42:44,628 --> 00:42:48,530
You are more valuable dead
to a company than alive.

808
00:42:49,833 --> 00:42:53,325
American Greetings, RR Donnelly & Sons,
and Proctor & Gamble

809
00:42:53,370 --> 00:42:56,134
are all having problems
with mortality.

810
00:42:56,173 --> 00:42:58,664
These 4 combined programs
are running at 50%

811
00:42:58,709 --> 00:43:00,199
of expected mortality.

812
00:43:00,244 --> 00:43:03,702
These clients are acutely aware
of this problem.

813
00:43:03,747 --> 00:43:06,443
Basically here the broker
is complaining

814
00:43:06,483 --> 00:43:08,883
that not enough
employees are dying.

815
00:43:08,919 --> 00:43:12,616
And therefore the investment returns
are not matching the projections.

816
00:43:12,656 --> 00:43:15,090
The broker writes
that NCC is running

817
00:43:15,125 --> 00:43:17,821
at 78% of expected mortality.

818
00:43:17,861 --> 00:43:21,729
Okay, so 78% of the people
we expected to die died.

819
00:43:21,765 --> 00:43:24,996
But the problem with that
is 3 of them were suicides.

820
00:43:25,035 --> 00:43:27,162
And you can't count
on that every year.

821
00:43:27,204 --> 00:43:29,229
Can you think of any other situation

822
00:43:29,273 --> 00:43:33,607
were you'd actually want
people to die?

823
00:43:33,644 --> 00:43:37,842
Combatants in war, I guess.

824
00:43:38,681 --> 00:43:41,681
When do you want people to die?

825
00:43:41,718 --> 00:43:43,345
I-I don't know.

826
00:43:43,387 --> 00:43:47,187
War situations,
terrorism situations.

827
00:43:49,126 --> 00:43:51,822
Drug trials, perhaps.
I don't know.

828
00:43:51,862 --> 00:43:54,456
I don't know.
That's an odd question.

829
00:43:54,498 --> 00:43:57,729
I didn't understand
how any of this could be legal.

830
00:43:57,768 --> 00:44:00,601
After all, there's a reason
that there's a law

831
00:44:00,637 --> 00:44:05,040
prohibiting me from taking out
a fire insurance policy on your house

832
00:44:05,075 --> 00:44:09,307
because I have a vested interest
in your house burning down.

833
00:44:09,346 --> 00:44:12,474
Since Attorney Myers had been
researching this for years,

834
00:44:12,516 --> 00:44:14,575
I asked him which companies
were profiting

835
00:44:14,618 --> 00:44:16,415
from these insurance policies.

836
00:44:16,453 --> 00:44:17,886
I don't know,
you don't know,

837
00:44:17,921 --> 00:44:20,549
because there's no place
you can go and find out

838
00:44:20,591 --> 00:44:24,220
whether your company
is a purchaser

839
00:44:24,261 --> 00:44:26,559
- of these types of products.
- Which ones do you know?

840
00:44:26,597 --> 00:44:28,292
The ones that we know
that have slipped out are

841
00:44:28,332 --> 00:44:30,357
Bank of America, Citibank,

842
00:44:30,400 --> 00:44:33,699
Wal-Mart, Winn-Dixie,
Proctor & Gamble,

843
00:44:33,737 --> 00:44:35,864
McDonnell Douglas, Hershey,

844
00:44:35,906 --> 00:44:38,875
Nestlé, AT&T
Southwestern Bell,

845
00:44:38,909 --> 00:44:40,968
Ameritech, American Express--

846
00:44:41,011 --> 00:44:43,070
- This is blue chip you're talking about.
- Yeah.

847
00:44:43,113 --> 00:44:46,310
These aren't fly-by-night companies
trying to do a scam here

848
00:44:46,350 --> 00:44:48,511
so they can collect a check
if one of their employees dies.

849
00:44:48,552 --> 00:44:51,851
There are probably
several million Americans

850
00:44:51,889 --> 00:44:55,723
who are covered by one of these policies
or have been at some point.

851
00:44:55,759 --> 00:44:57,021
There's a lot of it out there.

852
00:44:57,060 --> 00:44:59,221
This is Paul Smith.

853
00:44:59,263 --> 00:45:02,824
He used to be what is known
as a loyal employee.

854
00:45:02,866 --> 00:45:07,098
I worked for Wal-Mart for 18 years
and I gave them 110%.

855
00:45:07,137 --> 00:45:08,900
I mean, I loved that company.

856
00:45:08,939 --> 00:45:10,429
And as it turned out,
Wal-Mart took out

857
00:45:10,474 --> 00:45:13,534
over 350,000
life insurance policies

858
00:45:13,577 --> 00:45:15,704
on rank and file associates.

859
00:45:15,746 --> 00:45:16,940
These weren't executives.

860
00:45:16,980 --> 00:45:20,416
These were people like my wife,
a cake decorator for 18 months.

861
00:45:20,450 --> 00:45:24,045
That's the type of people they were taking
insurance policies out on.

862
00:45:24,087 --> 00:45:28,080
Paul's wife LaDonna left her job
at the Wal-Mart bakery

863
00:45:28,125 --> 00:45:30,923
so she could be a stay-at-home mom
for her 2 kids.

864
00:45:30,961 --> 00:45:34,124
She had asthma real real bad.

865
00:45:34,164 --> 00:45:36,098
She went into
the emergency room one night

866
00:45:36,133 --> 00:45:38,101
and a nurse comes out and says,
"Are you Mr. Smith?"

867
00:45:38,135 --> 00:45:39,625
And I said, "Yes."

868
00:45:39,670 --> 00:45:43,731
And she said, "We don't think
your wife's gonna make it."

869
00:45:43,774 --> 00:45:45,742
LaDonna slipped into a coma

870
00:45:45,776 --> 00:45:48,108
from which she would
never awaken.

871
00:45:48,145 --> 00:45:50,306
Her family rushed to the hospital,

872
00:45:50,347 --> 00:45:52,781
even though there was nothing
they could do to help.

873
00:45:52,816 --> 00:45:55,376
There was a wall here
and LaDonna's in the room

874
00:45:55,419 --> 00:45:56,852
on the other side of the wall.

875
00:45:56,887 --> 00:45:59,151
And Jessica kept saying,
"Where is she?"

876
00:45:59,189 --> 00:46:01,817
And I said, "She's right on
the other side of that wall."

877
00:46:01,858 --> 00:46:05,453
And Jessica said,
"Can we cut a hole in the wall

878
00:46:05,495 --> 00:46:07,986
so that we can see her?"

879
00:46:08,031 --> 00:46:10,056
And that just sticks with me.

880
00:46:10,100 --> 00:46:11,931
Do you remember that?

881
00:46:14,037 --> 00:46:18,406
We had to stay in there with her,
and so we'd write letters to her.

882
00:46:18,442 --> 00:46:22,902
"My dear wife, I miss you more
than any words can possibly say.

883
00:46:22,946 --> 00:46:24,504
You are my life.

884
00:46:24,548 --> 00:46:26,948
You always see beauty
in the simplest things.

885
00:46:26,984 --> 00:46:31,421
I've always admired you for that.
I wish I could have told you that more.

886
00:46:31,455 --> 00:46:33,719
I want you to come back
to me soon.

887
00:46:33,757 --> 00:46:36,749
I still have a lot left to learn
from you, baby doll.

888
00:46:36,793 --> 00:46:38,954
Your loving husband, Paul."

889
00:46:40,897 --> 00:46:43,331
You okay, Wesley?

890
00:46:44,735 --> 00:46:47,499
She was 26 years old.

891
00:46:47,537 --> 00:46:50,472
You're silly.

892
00:46:50,507 --> 00:46:54,170
The younger a person is,
the higher the benefit is

893
00:46:54,211 --> 00:46:57,009
because they're expected
to live longer.

894
00:46:57,047 --> 00:46:59,242
Women are also expected
to live longer than men.

895
00:46:59,282 --> 00:47:02,251
So the most valuable employee
to the company

896
00:47:02,285 --> 00:47:05,186
if they're dead,
is a young woman.

897
00:47:05,222 --> 00:47:06,814
LaDonna's death earned

898
00:47:06,857 --> 00:47:09,087
one of the richest corporations
in the world

899
00:47:09,126 --> 00:47:11,686
an extra $81,000.

900
00:47:11,728 --> 00:47:15,061
I was faced with over $100,000
worth of medical bills

901
00:47:15,098 --> 00:47:18,431
and a $6,000 funeral

902
00:47:18,468 --> 00:47:21,926
and Wal-Mart didn't offer a penny
to help with that.

903
00:47:21,972 --> 00:47:25,237
I did trust them.

904
00:47:25,275 --> 00:47:28,540
And never in a million years
would I have ever thought

905
00:47:28,578 --> 00:47:31,513
that somewhere
on a profit statement,

906
00:47:31,548 --> 00:47:34,540
"Dead associate, $81,000."

907
00:47:34,584 --> 00:47:38,577
Wal-Mart doesn't care about you.

908
00:47:38,622 --> 00:47:40,453
When someone passes away,

909
00:47:40,490 --> 00:47:43,288
they shouldn't get
something out of it.

910
00:47:53,970 --> 00:47:56,461
The common denominator
to each form of coverage

911
00:47:56,506 --> 00:47:58,531
is that when the employee dies,

912
00:47:58,575 --> 00:48:01,806
the employer gets paid
the insurance benefits.

913
00:48:01,845 --> 00:48:05,008
They're often referred to
as "dead peasant insurance."

914
00:48:05,048 --> 00:48:08,609
Dead peasants?
Why'd they use such a creepy name?

915
00:48:08,652 --> 00:48:11,780
It's very creepy.
I don't know what it means either.

916
00:48:11,822 --> 00:48:12,982
Dead is clear.

917
00:48:13,023 --> 00:48:15,753
That's the worker who's passed away,
so they're dead.

918
00:48:15,792 --> 00:48:18,226
Peasant, I don't know why
they chose that word.

919
00:48:18,261 --> 00:48:20,286
I don't know if it has
some historical significance

920
00:48:20,330 --> 00:48:23,322
or that's just the way they view
the relative value

921
00:48:23,366 --> 00:48:25,095
of the employees' lives.

922
00:48:25,135 --> 00:48:26,727
Dead peasants?

923
00:48:26,770 --> 00:48:28,897
Yeah, amongst themselves
that's what they call it.

924
00:48:30,474 --> 00:48:34,706
It's insulting to refer
to my husband like that.

925
00:48:41,852 --> 00:48:43,410
It turned out that Amegy Bank

926
00:48:43,453 --> 00:48:46,149
had a second
dead peasant policy on Dan,

927
00:48:46,189 --> 00:48:50,182
bringing their total take
to nearly $5 million.

928
00:48:53,029 --> 00:48:55,930
- Is capitalism a sin?
- Yes.

929
00:48:55,999 --> 00:48:58,559
Capitalism for me and for many of us

930
00:48:58,602 --> 00:49:01,935
at this present moment is an evil.

931
00:49:01,972 --> 00:49:05,738
It's contrary to all that's good.
It's contrary to the common good.

932
00:49:05,775 --> 00:49:08,005
It's contrary to compassion.

933
00:49:08,044 --> 00:49:11,013
It's contrary to
all of the major religions.

934
00:49:11,047 --> 00:49:15,108
Capitalism is precisely
what the holy books,

935
00:49:15,152 --> 00:49:19,816
our holy books in particular,
remind us is unjust

936
00:49:19,856 --> 00:49:22,825
and in some form and fashion,

937
00:49:22,859 --> 00:49:27,626
God will come down
and eradicate somehow.

938
00:49:27,664 --> 00:49:29,996
This was Father Dick Preston,

939
00:49:30,033 --> 00:49:33,366
the priest from Flint
who married my wife and me.

940
00:49:33,403 --> 00:49:35,564
Capitalism is wrong,

941
00:49:35,605 --> 00:49:39,336
and therefore
has to be eliminated.

942
00:49:39,376 --> 00:49:41,367
Eliminated?

943
00:49:41,411 --> 00:49:43,402
That might be a little harsh,

944
00:49:43,446 --> 00:49:45,437
so I decided to go
and talk to the priest

945
00:49:45,482 --> 00:49:47,780
that married my sister
and brother-in-law.

946
00:49:47,817 --> 00:49:50,115
I'm sure he would have
a more balanced approach

947
00:49:50,153 --> 00:49:52,280
when it came to capitalism.

948
00:49:52,322 --> 00:49:56,258
It is immoral, it is obscene,
it is outrageous.

949
00:49:56,293 --> 00:49:59,023
You know...

950
00:49:59,062 --> 00:50:01,394
it is really radical evil.

951
00:50:01,431 --> 00:50:03,729
It's radically evil.

952
00:50:04,267 --> 00:50:07,294
Does their boss know
that they're talking like this?

953
00:50:07,337 --> 00:50:10,363
I thought it best to go
and check this out with the bishop.

954
00:50:10,407 --> 00:50:12,671
Bishop Thomas Gumbleton:
The system doesn't seem to be

955
00:50:12,709 --> 00:50:16,475
providing for the well being
of all the people.

956
00:50:16,513 --> 00:50:19,414
And that's what makes it

957
00:50:19,449 --> 00:50:21,917
almost in its very nature

958
00:50:21,952 --> 00:50:25,888
something contrary
to Jesus who said,

959
00:50:25,922 --> 00:50:29,449
"Blessed are the poor,
woe to the rich."

960
00:50:29,492 --> 00:50:32,689
That's right out
of St. Luke's gospel.

961
00:50:32,729 --> 00:50:35,027
How have we put up
with this system for so long?

962
00:50:35,065 --> 00:50:37,226
I mean, it's--
they talk about--

963
00:50:37,267 --> 00:50:41,636
The system has built into it
what we call propaganda.

964
00:50:41,671 --> 00:50:43,901
I'm in awe of propaganda--

965
00:50:43,940 --> 00:50:46,909
the ability to convince people

966
00:50:46,943 --> 00:50:49,878
who are victimized
by this very system

967
00:50:49,913 --> 00:50:52,882
to support the system
and see it as good.

968
00:50:52,916 --> 00:50:56,317
We know that American capitalism
is morally right

969
00:50:56,353 --> 00:50:58,514
because its chief elements--

970
00:50:58,555 --> 00:51:01,615
private ownership,
the profit motive

971
00:51:01,658 --> 00:51:04,684
and the competitive market--
are wholesome and good.

972
00:51:04,728 --> 00:51:08,027
They are compatible with God's laws
and the teachings of the Bible.

973
00:51:09,032 --> 00:51:10,932
For as long as I can remember,

974
00:51:10,967 --> 00:51:14,562
I've been told that competition
and profit are good things.

975
00:51:14,604 --> 00:51:16,697
They are compatible with God's laws

976
00:51:16,740 --> 00:51:17,900
and the teachings of the Bible.

977
00:51:17,941 --> 00:51:21,274
And if increasing profits
means locking up a few kids

978
00:51:21,311 --> 00:51:23,438
or cashing in on the death
of an employee...

979
00:51:23,480 --> 00:51:26,313
Compatible with God's laws
and the teachings of the Bible.

980
00:51:26,349 --> 00:51:29,614
it is morally right to provide
for the stockholders.

981
00:51:29,653 --> 00:51:31,985
They are compatible with God's laws

982
00:51:32,022 --> 00:51:33,250
and the teachings of the Bible.

983
00:51:33,290 --> 00:51:36,521
Debt, eviction and exploitation.

984
00:51:36,559 --> 00:51:40,017
God's laws and the teachings of the Bible.

985
00:51:40,063 --> 00:51:42,998
What were we really
pledging our allegiance to?

986
00:51:43,033 --> 00:51:45,968
The profit motive.

987
00:51:46,002 --> 00:51:48,698
And so all good Americans
came to act as if they believed

988
00:51:48,738 --> 00:51:51,901
our capitalist economic system
was compatible

989
00:51:51,941 --> 00:51:54,273
with the teachings of the Bible.

990
00:52:02,552 --> 00:52:06,386
When I was a kid,
I wanted to be a priest.

991
00:52:06,423 --> 00:52:08,220
It wasn't because
of the fancy getups

992
00:52:08,258 --> 00:52:10,522
or the Knights of Columbus
escorts,

993
00:52:10,560 --> 00:52:13,859
or even the groovy nuns
who were so good to me.

994
00:52:14,898 --> 00:52:18,425
It was because of the priests
who went on the march from Selma,

995
00:52:18,468 --> 00:52:21,028
or tried to stop the war,

996
00:52:21,071 --> 00:52:24,529
or devoted their lives to the poor.

997
00:52:24,574 --> 00:52:28,533
They told me quite clearly
what Jesus said,

998
00:52:28,578 --> 00:52:32,947
that the first shall be last
and the last shall be first;

999
00:52:32,982 --> 00:52:35,678
That the rich man
will have a very hard time

1000
00:52:35,719 --> 00:52:37,778
getting into heaven;

1001
00:52:37,821 --> 00:52:41,655
That we will be judged by how
we treat the least among us;

1002
00:52:41,691 --> 00:52:44,319
And that there are no people
more important to God

1003
00:52:44,361 --> 00:52:46,886
than the poor.

1004
00:52:46,930 --> 00:52:49,455
Since that time,
it seems that Jesus got hijacked

1005
00:52:49,499 --> 00:52:52,468
by a lot of people who believe
that the son of God

1006
00:52:52,502 --> 00:52:56,871
was sent here to create
heaven on earth for the well-to-do.

1007
00:52:56,906 --> 00:52:59,101
I must have missed
that part of the Bible

1008
00:52:59,142 --> 00:53:02,441
where Jesus became a capitalist.

1009
00:53:06,750 --> 00:53:08,342
Please tell me, master,

1010
00:53:08,385 --> 00:53:11,149
what must I do
to have eternal life?

1011
00:53:11,187 --> 00:53:14,714
Go forth and maximize profits.

1012
00:53:16,559 --> 00:53:19,892
You say the Kingdom of Heaven
is at hand,

1013
00:53:19,929 --> 00:53:21,453
but when exactly will it come?

1014
00:53:21,498 --> 00:53:25,696
When you deregulate
the banking industry.

1015
00:53:25,735 --> 00:53:28,829
Help me.

1016
00:53:28,872 --> 00:53:31,397
I've been this way for 20 years.

1017
00:53:33,243 --> 00:53:36,735
I'm sorry, I cannot heal
your pre-existing condition.

1018
00:53:38,748 --> 00:53:40,409
He'll have to pay out of pocket.

1019
00:53:43,820 --> 00:53:46,311
Somehow, I don't think
Jesus came to earth

1020
00:53:46,356 --> 00:53:49,519
so he could ring the bell
at the New York Stock Exchange.

1021
00:53:49,559 --> 00:53:51,550
And yet,
from the very beginning,

1022
00:53:51,594 --> 00:53:54,427
the rich have claimed him
for their own.

1023
00:53:54,464 --> 00:53:58,264
When I'm on Wall Street
and I realize

1024
00:53:58,301 --> 00:54:02,431
that that's the very nerve center
of American capitalism,

1025
00:54:02,472 --> 00:54:06,135
and I realize
what capitalism has done

1026
00:54:06,176 --> 00:54:09,805
for working people in America,
to me that's a holy place.

1027
00:54:09,846 --> 00:54:11,006
Let me add to it.

1028
00:54:11,047 --> 00:54:15,074
Over the whole duration of the Iraq war
and the terror war,

1029
00:54:15,118 --> 00:54:18,952
you look at the world's stock markets
and you look at the world economy,

1030
00:54:18,988 --> 00:54:22,947
and despite these horrible pockets
of unrest and killing and murdering

1031
00:54:22,992 --> 00:54:25,893
that we've been describing,
it's never been better.

1032
00:54:25,929 --> 00:54:27,863
The global economy
has never been better

1033
00:54:27,897 --> 00:54:30,525
and the global stock markets
have never been better, Jimmy.

1034
00:54:30,567 --> 00:54:32,592
It is either a God-given miracle

1035
00:54:32,635 --> 00:54:34,603
or it has something to do
with the victories

1036
00:54:34,637 --> 00:54:37,003
of the spreading world
of capitalism or both.

1037
00:54:37,040 --> 00:54:38,974
They think
Wall Street's a holy place.

1038
00:54:39,008 --> 00:54:41,943
What do you think
Jesus would think of capitalism?

1039
00:54:41,978 --> 00:54:46,347
I think he would
simply refuse to--

1040
00:54:46,382 --> 00:54:49,619
to be part of it.

1041
00:54:50,787 --> 00:54:53,654
Jesus would refuse
to be part of it,

1042
00:54:53,690 --> 00:54:55,658
but he probably had
a special place up there

1043
00:54:55,692 --> 00:54:58,627
for whoever leaked
a secret Citibank memo

1044
00:54:58,661 --> 00:55:02,028
about their plan to rule the world.

1045
00:55:02,065 --> 00:55:04,056
Back in 2005 and 2006,

1046
00:55:04,100 --> 00:55:06,432
Citigroup wrote
3 confidential memos

1047
00:55:06,469 --> 00:55:10,929
to their wealthiest investors
about how things were going.

1048
00:55:10,974 --> 00:55:13,374
They reached the conclusion
that the United States

1049
00:55:13,409 --> 00:55:15,639
was no longer
really a democracy,

1050
00:55:15,678 --> 00:55:18,442
but had become a plutonomy--

1051
00:55:18,481 --> 00:55:21,575
a society controlled exclusively
by and for the benefit

1052
00:55:21,618 --> 00:55:24,712
of the top 1 %
of the population

1053
00:55:24,754 --> 00:55:26,847
who now had
more financial wealth

1054
00:55:26,890 --> 00:55:30,519
than the bottom 95% combined.

1055
00:55:30,560 --> 00:55:33,791
The memo gloated about the growing gap
between rich and poor

1056
00:55:33,830 --> 00:55:37,288
and how they were now
the new aristocracy

1057
00:55:37,333 --> 00:55:41,269
and that there was no end in sight
for the gravy train they were on.

1058
00:55:41,304 --> 00:55:44,865
There was, though,
one problem.

1059
00:55:44,908 --> 00:55:46,432
According to Citigroup,

1060
00:55:46,476 --> 00:55:49,070
the most potent
and short-term threat

1061
00:55:49,112 --> 00:55:50,909
would be societies demanding

1062
00:55:50,947 --> 00:55:53,541
a more equitable share
of the wealth.

1063
00:55:53,583 --> 00:55:57,952
In other words,
the peasants might revolt.

1064
00:55:57,987 --> 00:56:00,353
Citigroup lamented
that the non-rich

1065
00:56:00,390 --> 00:56:02,858
might not have
much economic power,

1066
00:56:02,892 --> 00:56:06,419
but they do have
equal voting power with the rich.

1067
00:56:06,462 --> 00:56:09,431
One person, one vote.

1068
00:56:09,465 --> 00:56:12,127
And that's what
really scares them--

1069
00:56:12,168 --> 00:56:14,602
that we can still vote.

1070
00:56:14,637 --> 00:56:17,936
In fact, we have
99% of the votes

1071
00:56:17,974 --> 00:56:20,772
and they only have 1%.

1072
00:56:23,846 --> 00:56:27,805
So why do the 99%
put up with this?

1073
00:56:27,850 --> 00:56:31,286
According to Citigroup,
it's because the majority of the electorate

1074
00:56:31,321 --> 00:56:33,812
believe that someday
they will have a chance

1075
00:56:33,856 --> 00:56:36,381
of becoming
well-to-do themselves

1076
00:56:36,426 --> 00:56:39,589
if they just keep trying
hard enough.

1077
00:56:41,931 --> 00:56:44,229
The wealthy were pleased
that so many people

1078
00:56:44,267 --> 00:56:47,100
had bought in
to the American Dream

1079
00:56:47,136 --> 00:56:50,196
while they, the rich,
had no intention

1080
00:56:50,239 --> 00:56:53,140
of ever sharing it with anyone.

1081
00:56:53,176 --> 00:56:56,475
I think capitalism is a lot more
important than democracy.

1082
00:56:56,512 --> 00:56:58,878
I'm not even a big believer
in democracy.

1083
00:56:58,915 --> 00:57:02,510
I always say that democracy is--
can be 2 wolves and a sheep

1084
00:57:02,552 --> 00:57:04,213
deciding on what to have
for dinner.

1085
00:57:04,253 --> 00:57:07,484
This is Stephen Moore--
no relation--

1086
00:57:07,523 --> 00:57:09,957
a columnist
and an editorial board member

1087
00:57:09,993 --> 00:57:11,756
of "The Wall Street Journal,"

1088
00:57:11,794 --> 00:57:15,230
the daily bible
of corporate America.

1089
00:57:15,264 --> 00:57:18,324
Look, I'm in favor of people
having the right to vote

1090
00:57:18,368 --> 00:57:20,836
and things like that, but you know
there are a lot of countries

1091
00:57:20,870 --> 00:57:24,738
that have the right to vote
that are still poor.

1092
00:57:24,774 --> 00:57:28,141
Democracy doesn't always lead
to a good economy

1093
00:57:28,177 --> 00:57:30,111
or even a good political system.

1094
00:57:30,146 --> 00:57:33,513
With capitalism, you are free
to do what you want,

1095
00:57:33,549 --> 00:57:35,608
to make whatever you want
out of yourself.

1096
00:57:35,652 --> 00:57:37,176
It doesn't mean
you're gonna succeed.

1097
00:57:37,220 --> 00:57:41,623
Remember, the US Constitution
does not guarantee happiness.

1098
00:57:42,258 --> 00:57:44,286
The Constitution.

1099
00:57:44,327 --> 00:57:48,093
All my life I've heard that America
is a capitalist country.

1100
00:57:48,131 --> 00:57:52,397
So I went to see the original Constitution
and check out if it was true.

1101
00:57:52,435 --> 00:57:55,871
I'm trying to see where it sets up
our economic system,

1102
00:57:55,905 --> 00:57:59,136
like where it says we have
a capitalist economy.

1103
00:57:59,175 --> 00:58:01,336
The jurisdiction.

1104
00:58:01,377 --> 00:58:03,174
- Judicial part of the--
- Down there?

1105
00:58:03,212 --> 00:58:07,012
There was no mention
of free market or free enterprise

1106
00:58:07,050 --> 00:58:09,644
or capitalism anywhere.

1107
00:58:10,687 --> 00:58:13,952
In fact, all I saw was
"We the people,"

1108
00:58:13,990 --> 00:58:16,584
something about
"a more perfect union,"

1109
00:58:16,626 --> 00:58:19,993
and "promoting
the general welfare."

1110
00:58:20,029 --> 00:58:24,523
Welfare, union, we?

1111
00:58:24,567 --> 00:58:26,967
That sounded like that other -ism.

1112
00:58:27,003 --> 00:58:30,439
But no, that's democracy.

1113
00:58:30,473 --> 00:58:33,175
And I began to wonder,
"What would it be like

1114
00:58:33,242 --> 00:58:36,575
if the workplace
was a democracy?"

1115
00:58:36,612 --> 00:58:39,945
There's always been a big separation
between how the country is run

1116
00:58:39,982 --> 00:58:43,213
and how businesses
are supposed to run.

1117
00:58:43,252 --> 00:58:44,446
It's true.

1118
00:58:44,487 --> 00:58:46,352
There seems to be a disconnect

1119
00:58:46,389 --> 00:58:48,721
between our professed love
of democracy

1120
00:58:48,758 --> 00:58:51,784
and how we're so willing
to accept a dictatorship

1121
00:58:51,828 --> 00:58:54,695
every day we show up to work.

1122
00:58:54,731 --> 00:58:58,531
It's not that way
at Isthmus Engineering in Wisconsin.

1123
00:58:58,568 --> 00:59:02,402
They design and build
robotic machines for industry.

1124
00:59:02,438 --> 00:59:05,601
It's a $15 million-a-year business.

1125
00:59:05,641 --> 00:59:07,438
All of the workers

1126
00:59:07,477 --> 00:59:10,810
are the owners of the business.

1127
00:59:10,847 --> 00:59:14,408
He's not talking about
some bullshit stock option.

1128
00:59:14,450 --> 00:59:17,851
He means they're the true owners.

1129
00:59:17,887 --> 00:59:20,720
And it's a democratically-run
operation where every member

1130
00:59:20,757 --> 00:59:23,726
has one vote and an equal say.

1131
00:59:23,760 --> 00:59:26,024
- All in favor?
- All in favor?

1132
00:59:26,062 --> 00:59:29,088
It takes the money
out of the equation.

1133
00:59:29,132 --> 00:59:31,157
By taking the money
out of the equation

1134
00:59:31,200 --> 00:59:33,430
so that they can call the shots,

1135
00:59:33,469 --> 00:59:35,801
they end up making more money.

1136
00:59:35,838 --> 00:59:37,466
Cool?

1137
00:59:42,145 --> 00:59:44,943
And how patriotic
that they want to extend

1138
00:59:44,981 --> 00:59:48,815
their love of American democracy
to their job.

1139
00:59:55,124 --> 00:59:57,058
Just imagine if the place
where you worked

1140
00:59:57,093 --> 01:00:00,256
was run by you
and your fellow workers.

1141
01:00:00,296 --> 01:00:02,161
You probably wouldn't
lay off your coworkers

1142
01:00:02,198 --> 01:00:05,133
to increase the value
of your stock, would you?

1143
01:00:05,168 --> 01:00:06,635
Or give yourself
a pay raise

1144
01:00:06,669 --> 01:00:09,536
while making your coworkers
take a pay cut.

1145
01:00:09,572 --> 01:00:11,437
We don't really do that here.

1146
01:00:11,474 --> 01:00:15,069
You really can't because everyone else
would be looking at you

1147
01:00:15,111 --> 01:00:17,671
saying, "Why is this guy
so fricking greedy?"

1148
01:00:17,713 --> 01:00:20,307
You know,
it would be too obvious.

1149
01:00:20,349 --> 01:00:22,214
The bottom line is you've
got plenty of people

1150
01:00:22,251 --> 01:00:24,048
who roll up their sleeves
every day and go to work.

1151
01:00:24,086 --> 01:00:25,986
But if there's someone
way up there on the chain

1152
01:00:26,022 --> 01:00:29,048
that collects all the extra money,
that's not fair.

1153
01:00:30,291 --> 01:00:32,857
Fairness in the workplace--

1154
01:00:32,895 --> 01:00:35,227
what a novel idea.

1155
01:00:36,666 --> 01:00:39,897
Out in California,
there's a bread factory

1156
01:00:39,936 --> 01:00:43,497
where workers make thousands
of loaves of bread every day

1157
01:00:43,539 --> 01:00:45,530
The more hours you work towards

1158
01:00:45,575 --> 01:00:46,872
the benefit
of the co-op,

1159
01:00:46,909 --> 01:00:49,776
the more you share
in the profits.

1160
01:00:49,812 --> 01:00:52,007
The workers are happy here.

1161
01:00:52,048 --> 01:00:54,516
No big Is, little yous.
Everyone's the same.

1162
01:00:54,550 --> 01:00:58,042
Me as the CEO,
I get the same share

1163
01:00:58,087 --> 01:01:00,112
that anybody else does.

1164
01:01:00,156 --> 01:01:01,953
And that has proven

1165
01:01:01,991 --> 01:01:04,323
to be very lucrative
for us as workers.

1166
01:01:06,162 --> 01:01:10,724
Assembly-line workers here
earn over $65,000 a year,

1167
01:01:10,766 --> 01:01:12,859
more than 3 times the pay

1168
01:01:12,902 --> 01:01:15,462
for a starting pilot
at American Eagle.

1169
01:01:15,504 --> 01:01:18,302
I'm just hoping
that people take notice

1170
01:01:18,341 --> 01:01:20,502
of this type
of organizational activity

1171
01:01:20,543 --> 01:01:23,944
and start considering it
as an alternative.

1172
01:01:23,980 --> 01:01:25,311
Why do you want
to get rich?

1173
01:01:25,348 --> 01:01:27,282
How many cars do
you really need in life?

1174
01:01:27,316 --> 01:01:31,912
Clearly, he's not a car guy,
but that's okay.

1175
01:01:31,954 --> 01:01:35,481
His bread factory and hundreds of other
worker-owned businesses

1176
01:01:35,524 --> 01:01:39,119
are proof that people aren't always
motivated by profit.

1177
01:01:41,998 --> 01:01:44,626
An historic victory over a dread disease.

1178
01:01:44,667 --> 01:01:48,034
Instead of using his genius
to make a ton of money,

1179
01:01:48,070 --> 01:01:51,335
Dr. Jonas Salk spent
all of his time

1180
01:01:51,374 --> 01:01:53,865
putting monkey kidneys
in a blender

1181
01:01:53,910 --> 01:01:55,969
trying to find a cure
for polio.

1182
01:01:56,012 --> 01:02:00,881
And when he did,
he decided to give it away for free.

1183
01:02:00,917 --> 01:02:03,977
This man could have been rich
many times over

1184
01:02:04,020 --> 01:02:07,353
had he sold his vaccine
to a pharmaceutical company.

1185
01:02:07,390 --> 01:02:09,824
But he thought
his talents should be used

1186
01:02:09,859 --> 01:02:11,053
for the greater good.

1187
01:02:11,093 --> 01:02:14,028
And the decent salary
he made as a doctor

1188
01:02:14,063 --> 01:02:16,463
and a research professor
was enough for him to live

1189
01:02:16,499 --> 01:02:18,558
a comfortable life.

1190
01:02:18,601 --> 01:02:21,001
Who owns the patent
on this vaccine?

1191
01:02:21,037 --> 01:02:23,005
Well, the people,
I would say.

1192
01:02:23,039 --> 01:02:26,600
There is no patent.
Would you patent the sun?

1193
01:02:26,642 --> 01:02:30,476
Yes, we've come a long way
since the days of Dr. Salk.

1194
01:02:30,513 --> 01:02:34,643
Because today our best minds
are used for something else.

1195
01:02:35,084 --> 01:02:38,801
Where do we send our top
math and science people?

1196
01:02:39,054 --> 01:02:40,085
Into finance.

1197
01:02:40,122 --> 01:02:42,590
They don't go into
science in America.

1198
01:02:42,625 --> 01:02:45,321
They go to Wall Street.

1199
01:02:45,361 --> 01:02:48,421
Today's students,
unlike in Dr. Salk's time,

1200
01:02:48,464 --> 01:02:51,024
can graduate from college
with a student loan debt

1201
01:02:51,067 --> 01:02:54,093
of up to $100,000 or more.

1202
01:02:54,136 --> 01:02:56,434
These students are then
beholden to the banks

1203
01:02:56,472 --> 01:02:59,441
for the next 20 years.

1204
01:02:59,475 --> 01:03:02,308
And the best way for them
to pay off these banks

1205
01:03:02,345 --> 01:03:04,279
is to go to work for them

1206
01:03:04,313 --> 01:03:06,941
instead of working
for the common good.

1207
01:03:06,983 --> 01:03:11,352
We've taken people that could
be enormously productive--

1208
01:03:11,387 --> 01:03:13,014
just what we're short of
in America--

1209
01:03:13,055 --> 01:03:16,081
and we take them and we
put them in an activity

1210
01:03:16,125 --> 01:03:18,116
that isn't simply less
productive,

1211
01:03:18,160 --> 01:03:20,958
but where they're
actually destructive;

1212
01:03:20,997 --> 01:03:24,797
where actually every day they work,
they make the world worse.

1213
01:03:24,834 --> 01:03:27,894
So what exactly were the top
students from Harvard

1214
01:03:27,937 --> 01:03:29,928
and other schools
working on these days?

1215
01:03:29,972 --> 01:03:31,997
Derivatives... derivatives...
derivatives... derivatives...

1216
01:03:32,041 --> 01:03:34,441
Credit default swaps.

1217
01:03:34,477 --> 01:03:36,502
I can't make any sense
out of this.

1218
01:03:36,545 --> 01:03:38,308
I might as well quit.

1219
01:03:38,397 --> 01:03:40,097
That's exactly how I felt

1220
01:03:40,190 --> 01:03:42,351
when I started hearing
these new terms.

1221
01:03:42,393 --> 01:03:46,523
So I went down to the New York Stock
Exchange to get some answers.

1222
01:03:46,563 --> 01:03:48,292
Sir, can you explain
derivatives to me?

1223
01:03:48,332 --> 01:03:50,562
Can anybody explain
derivatives or credit default swaps?

1224
01:03:50,601 --> 01:03:51,829
Can someone explain
to me what these are?

1225
01:03:51,869 --> 01:03:54,099
Sir, can you tell me what
a credit default swap is?

1226
01:03:54,138 --> 01:03:55,662
Can you explain
a derivative to me?

1227
01:03:55,706 --> 01:03:57,173
Can you tell me
what a derivative is?

1228
01:03:57,207 --> 01:03:59,471
- Nobody'll talk to me.
